Define boundary Function for Decision Boundaries and Simulate Data

# input: 
# model: classification model
# data: training set
# class: response variable

boundary <- function(model, data, class = NULL, predict_type = "class",
  resolution = 100, showgrid = TRUE, ...) {

  if(!is.null(class)) cl <- data[,class] else cl <- 1
  data <- data[,1:2]
  k <- length(unique(cl))

  plot(data, col = as.integer(cl)+1L, pch = as.integer(cl)+1L, ...)

  # make grid
  r <- sapply(data, range, na.rm = TRUE)
  xs <- seq(r[1,1], r[2,1], length.out = resolution)
  ys <- seq(r[1,2], r[2,2], length.out = resolution)
  g <- cbind(rep(xs, each=resolution), rep(ys, time = resolution))
  colnames(g) <- colnames(r)
  g <- as.data.frame(g)

  ### guess how to get class labels from predict
  ### (unfortunately not very consistent between models)
  p <- predict(model, g, type = predict_type)
  if(is.list(p)) p <- p$class
  p <- as.factor(p)

  if(showgrid) points(g, col = as.integer(p)+1L, pch = ".")

  z <- matrix(as.integer(p), nrow = resolution, byrow = TRUE)
  contour(xs, ys, z, add = TRUE, drawlabels = FALSE,
    lwd = 2, levels = (1:(k-1))+.5)

  invisible(z)
}

Model 3: Logistics Regression

# Split the data into training and testing sets
set.seed(123) # For reproducibility
index <- createDataPartition(myData$affordable, p = 0.7, list = FALSE)
trainData <- myData[index, ]
testData <- myData[-index, ]

train_x <- trainData %>% select(cur_passengers,distance) 
test_x <- testData %>% select(cur_passengers,distance) 

# Fit the logistic regression model
model1 <- glm(affordable ~ cur_passengers + distance, data = trainData, family=binomial(link='logit'))

# Summary of the model to interpret coefficients
summary(model1)

class(model1) <- c("lr", class(model1))

predict.lr <- function(object, newdata, ...)predict.glm(object, newdata, type = "response") > 0.511
boundary_data <- myData %>% select(cur_passengers, distance, affordable)
boundary(model1, boundary_data, class = "affordable", main = "Logistic Regression")

# model1$deviance: Residual deviance
# model1$null.deviance: Null deviance
G <- model1$null.deviance - model1$deviance

# model1$df.residual: degree of freedom of residual deviance
# model1$df.null: degree of freedom of null deviance
df <- model1$df.null - model1$df.residual

# calculate the p-value(upper-side p-value)
p <- pchisq(q = G, df = df, lower.tail = F)
p
